The paper deals with communication channels and information theory, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The use of side information and constraints also suggests that it could belong to the cs.SI (Signal Processing) sub-category. The study of capacity bounds and regions suggests that it could belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category. The mention of a binary symmetric broadcast channel suggests that it could belong to the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category. Finally, the use of generalized non-symmetrizability condition suggests that it could belong to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category.
